Sweetheart Deal: Chapter Twenty-Nine - Wake-up Call

Welcome to Nuevo Carcangel, circa 2174. A century has passed since a plague killed half of humanity. No one living now knows why some of the survivors are called chimeras, nor how the plague created them - if it did.
Christina Marlowe, a private investigator and a fox-type chimera, has other concerns. She's living in one of the biggest city-states. What technology used to exist is gone. She knows the trains and streetcars, her trusty revolver, and that she needs a big case.
Nathaniel Berrymount may be it. He's nervous at first and rightly so. The signs point to a sweetheart deal that's meant to collapse, leaving the victor with everything.
Marlowe will have to think and talk fast as events pile up. A Boss wants his blueprints back. What do the buns of The Warren want? And can she keep her client from falling for her?

In this chapter, mornings are a bit different when you wake up inside the six city blocks that make up The Warren. Sunlight doesn't exist. Likewise, Marlowe doesn't have to think about if the cats have the numbers to besiege the place - they don't. But as she rolls out of a cot, what she'd better put her brain to is what's on the other side of the door. Buns, and with schemes more voluminous than her vixie tail.
They'll learn that Marlowe doesn't always pull her punches.

This is a big pet peeve of mine and I end up hating it whichever way it's done of these two. The jargon blabber method is the worst, unless you're trying to be comedic. What I do is I try to research an IRL problem and see how the professional would solve it, then go about the process by keeping it vague enough that it looks plausible, but without explaining it in depth. So if I'm showing someone crafting a bomb or making a medicine with herbs, or showing some other skill, I'll try to make it feel like you're looking at a skilled worker doing something plausible (because it's referenced from real life) even if you don't really understand what he's doing.

A lot of sci-fi does go full jargon, and successfully. The key is building up the reader so that they follow.
Hard sci-fi and almost all military fiction are stuffed with jargon.
Courtroom or medical fiction? Like a historical novel, so much fucking jargon.
I could go on.

Take happy's story. In one word -buckner - he does paragraphs of worldbuilding.
Bill buckner, first base for the bottom Red Sox, 1986 world series. A ground ball rolls through his legs and the game, and series, turns on it.
One of baseball's most infamous plays, and all the implications are a bonus. In story, the context lets me know that a buckner is some kind of error or fuckup.

A little jargon or slang like that goes a long way.

A true and good point
I edit with a method that is good at reducing this. All non-action descriptions and narrations get highlighted in red.
About the only time I allow multiple paragraphs of it is when a character is alone or would be thinking as they move between places.
As for the 'boring the reader' bit, I've found some people will complain about anything. A better measure is to keep a good pace in you chapters & scenes. If something is important enough and you need them to take note, your pace will fit that.
As for essay? As above.
On the broader scale, I feel that if there's a choice between what the reader wants and what the story needs, do what you can to sprinkle the first on the second. But don't break your story in the process.
